A stack is a data structure that follows the LIFO (last in, first out) principle. It uses last in, first out to remove elements from the stack. The most recent element added to the stack is the first element removed. A stack can be implemented using an array or linked list.

Pseudocode for a stack:
```
class Stack {
    var elements = [] # array or linked list

    def push(element) {
        elements.append(element) # add element to the stack
    }

    def pop() {
        return elements.removeLast() # remove and return the most recent element added to the stack
    }

    def isEmpty() {
        return elements.isEmpty() # check if the stack is empty
    }
}
```
Here's an example implementation of a stack using Java:
```
public class Stack {
    private Node top;

    public Stack() {
        top = null;
    }

    public void push(int element) {
        Node newNode = new Node(element);

        if (top == null) {
            top = newNode;
        } else {
            newNode.next = top;
            top = newNode;
        }
    }

    public int pop() {
        if (!isEmpty()) {
            top = top.next;
            return top.data;
        }
        return -1;
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return top == null;
    }
}
```
